<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="TolE0128">
<l>eppeyar muṉṉarum valleḻuttu varuvaḻi</l>
<l>akkiṉ iṟutimeym micaiyoṭuṅ keṭumē</l>
<l>kuṟṟiya lukara muṟṟat tōṉṟātu</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>The final consonant of <foreign xml:lang="ta">akku</foreign> disappears when</l>
<l>[<foreign xml:lang="ta">akku</foreign>] is inserted between any noun and</l>
<l>[a word beginning] with plosive, [and]</l>
<l>the over-short <foreign xml:lang="ta">-u</foreign> [of <foreign xml:lang="ta">akku</foreign>] disappears completely.<note place="foot">E.g. <foreign xml:lang="ta">tamiḻ + akku + kūttu &gt; tamiḻakkūttu.</foreign>
          There are some problems with the interpretation of this aphorism. According to later
          commentators, this happens not only before stops, but before other consonants, too, e.g. <foreign xml:lang="ta">tamiḻ + akku + nūl &gt; tamiḻanūl., tamiḻ + akku + yāppu &gt; tamiḻayāppu.</foreign> I agree with the interpretation of Iḷamp. The cases quoted by later commentators obviously involve a different matter.</note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
